english:
  title: Preface to Sending Off Baek Joong-won, Compiler of Records, as He Transports the Historical Records to Dry in the Sun at Chiljangsaji Temple
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I once read in the Analects the Master's words: "I have seen the historian leave blanks in his records." From this I have come to understand that history must employ language to record events, yet cannot let language multiply and obscure the truth. Better to have sparse language than rich language that loses reality. In the declining days of Zhou, language exceeded substance, and the Master was deeply grieved by this. Thus in the Book of Documents he pruned away confusion and excess, and in the Spring and Autumn Annals he used but one word to judge each matter. The Documents and the Spring and Autumn are history itself. Moreover, because the sage refined and edited them with his brush and blade, they became Classics. Zuo Qiuming supported the sage's brush with his commentary-wings, yet because he did not fully grasp analogy, he could not escape the faults of extravagance and exaggeration. Sima Qian, styled Zichang, unleashed his unrestrained and magnificent spirit to produce writing that is grand, solid, elegant and vigorous—thus he is called a great historian. Yet because he did not follow the method of the Spring and Autumn Annals, his records contain many contradictions and confused judgments, and the righteous lament this. If even these two masters faltered thus, what of all the others? This shows how history does not prize abundance of language. And yet history settles the rights and wrongs of all under heaven and leaves instruction and warning for ten thousand ages. From above—the successes and failures of rulers and ministers in governance—to below—the beauty and ugliness of common customs and habits, the order and chaos of ancient and modern times, the rise and fall of nations, all the great and small, beginning and end, subtlety and complexity of human affairs; extending far even to the changes of heaven and earth, sun and moon, wind and thunder, frost and hail; and reaching minutely even to the peculiarities of grass and wood, birds and beasts, feathers and scales—nothing fails to be recorded with each matter, becoming trust for posterity. Could this be accomplished without language? Thus history cannot neglect language either. Then how shall this be resolved? It lies solely in illuminating principle. When principle shines clear, words must be concise yet complete, and language must be direct and truthful. By this measure weighing the affairs of all under heaven—as a scale balances weight, as a ruler measures length, as a torch illuminates, as a tortoise-shell divines—right and wrong do not err, and instruction becomes manifest.

    Baek Joong-won of Gyeongsan, serving at the National Academy, has studied the Spring and Autumn Annals, probing deeply into the meaning of editorial refinement. His grasp of principle shines luminously, and thus his language flourishes splendidly. Upon passing the great examination and being recommended by the Court of Refined Letters, he was appointed to the historical office. For years now he has wielded praise and blame through his writing, guided by principle and righteousness. Now receiving the command to sun the historical records, he takes up his brush and departs. The gentleman-scholars composed verses to send him off, and asked me to write this preface. I said: "Alas! Our Master, in composing the Spring and Autumn Annals, sought to address a declining age. The histories of successive dynasties too may reveal the transformations of the world.

    "Our nation has held the Eastern lands for several hundred years. In the beginning, the national records were stored in the Haeinsa Temple on Mount Gaya—a precaution against loss should chaos befall later generations. Mount Gaya lies farthest and most perilously distant from the capital, and Haeinsa sits most secluded and deeply sheltered within Gaya. Thus though the nation has faced upheaval, warfare has never reached there—our ancestors' foresight was indeed far-reaching. Yet recently, in controlling the Japanese invaders, military discipline was lost. They penetrated deep, raiding provinces and counties. Gaya itself nearly fell to siege. In autumn of Hongwu's jimiyear, the records were moved north across the ridge to Gaecheonsa Temple in Chungju. Then this summer, in the gyehae year, the invaders pressed again upon counties near Chungju, and in the seventh month, the records were moved once more from Gaecheonsa to Chiljangsaji Temple in Jukju. A remote and dangerous place offers no sure refuge; the enemy's daring to penetrate so deeply shows how the world transforms. Here I feel a deep stirring. In ancient times, as Zhou declined and rebels arose, the Master, fearing this, composed the Spring and Autumn Annals. Now chaos reaches its extreme and the age transforms most radically. I know Joong-won's brush will mark these times with singular power. When Joong-won studied at the Academy, I served as its director; now we serve together in the historical office. The request for this preface I cannot in good conscience refuse. I therefore commit to writing what I once learned from the Analects and what I feel upon witnessing these times, making this preface."
  footnotes:
    - The reference to the Master's words about the historian leaving blanks comes from Analects 15.25, where Confucius expresses his reluctance to condemn even those who act wrongly, compared to the historian who leaves blank spaces rather than record uncertain matters.
    - Mount Gaya (Gayasan) and Haeinsa Temple were indeed remote locations in medieval Korea, chosen specifically to preserve the national historical records during periods of foreign invasion and civil unrest.
    - The dates mentioned (Hongwu jimiyear and gyehae year) correspond to 1379 and 1383 CE respectively, periods when Japanese pirate raids (wakō) severely threatened Korean coastal and inland regions.
    - Gwon Geun served as Director (祭酒) of the National Academy (Taehak) and later held positions in the historical office, giving him authority to comment on both scholarship and state records.
